  "prompt": "This sentence has two verbs: \"will look\u201d and \"go.\u201d How do I understand this grammatical construct?",
  "response": "The sentence structure you're referring to likely involves a combination of a future tense verb and a base form (bare infinitive) of another verb. This is a common construct in English, often used to express future intentions or plans.\n\n1. **\"Will look\"**: This is a simple future tense construction. \"Will\" is a modal verb used to indicate future actions or intentions, and \"look\" is the main verb in its base form.\n\n2. **\"Go\"**: Without the specific sentence context, it seems that \"go\" is being used as part of an infinitive phrase or a second action related to the first.\n\nIn many cases, such constructs will follow a pattern like \"will look to go\" or \"will look and go.\" Here's how they might work:\n\n- **\"Will look to go\"**: This suggests that the subject intends to search or plan for the opportunity to go somewhere or do something in the future.\n\n- **\"Will look and go\"**: This might imply two consecutive actions, where the subject will first \"look\" (possibly meaning \"consider\" or \"examine\") and then \"go.\"\n\nWithout the complete sentence, it's challenging to give a precise grammatical analysis, but the key takeaway is that \"will\" marks future intention, \"look\" is a present tense verb, and \"go\" likely represents an action that complements \"look.\" If you provide the complete sentence, I could offer more specific guidance.",
